## Saving Data on the Device
React Native uses `AsyncStorage` (or similar libraries) to save key-value data persistently on the phone.

It is **asynchronous** (returns a Promise), unlike `localStorage` on the web.

```javascript
// Saving
await AsyncStorage.setItem('@theme', 'dark');

// Reading
const theme = await AsyncStorage.getItem('@theme');
```

## Smooth UI Transitions
React Native's `Animated` API allows for fluid, 60fps animations.

Instead of standard `View` or `Text`, you must use `Animated.View` or `Animated.Text` to apply animated styles.

```javascript
// Starting value
const fadeAnim = useRef(new Animated.Value(0)).current;

// Trigger animation
Animated.timing(fadeAnim, {
  toValue: 1,
  duration: 1000,
  useNativeDriver: true // Moves work off the JS thread
}).start();
```

